post_cb({"39313362": {"ViewCount": "123", "Body": "<p>Can I use the first parameter as a default for the second parameter, like this?</p>\n<pre><code>int do_something(int a, int b = a + 1){\n    /* ... */\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>My compiler doesn't seem to like it, so perhaps it's not allowed.</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "39313419", "Title": "C++ default a parameter to another parameter", "CreationDate": "2016-09-04T03:46:48.400", "Id": "39313362", "CommentCount": "1", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastActivityDate": "2016-09-04T04:02:54.040", "Score": "4", "OwnerUserId": "1021959", "Tags": "<c++><parameters>", "AnswerCount": "3"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_39313362_39313376_0": {"length": 13, "quality": 0.9285714285714286, "section_id": 3260}}, "n3337": {"so_39313362_39313376_0": {"length": 13, "quality": 0.9285714285714286, "section_id": 3132}}}, "39313419": {"PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Your question has already been answered (it is not allowed), but in case you didn't realize, the workaround is trivial with function overloading.</p>\n<pre><code>int do_something(int a, int b){\n    /* ... */\n}\n\nint do_something(int a) {\n    return do_something(a, a + 1);\n}\n</code></pre>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2016-09-04T03:58:55.250", "Id": "39313419", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2016-09-04T03:58:55.250", "ParentId": "39313362", "Score": "11", "OwnerUserId": "440119"}, "39313376": {"PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>It is not allowed.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_39313362_39313376_0\">The order of evaluation of function arguments is unspecified. Consequently, parameters of a\n  function shall not be used in a default argument, even if they are not evaluated.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>(from [dcl.fct.default]/9 in C++14)</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2016-09-04T03:49:51.493", "Id": "39313376", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2016-09-04T03:49:51.493", "ParentId": "39313362", "Score": "9", "OwnerUserId": "481267"}, "39313417": {"PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>if I were U I would do this</p>\n<pre><code>int do_something(int a, int b){\n    b = a + 1;\n    /* ... */\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>But the b value is not gonna change after the function complete executing. \nPassing b by reference will work. (int &amp;b)</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2016-09-04T03:58:32.823", "Id": "39313417", "CommentCount": "2", "CreationDate": "2016-09-04T03:58:32.823", "ParentId": "39313362", "Score": "-5", "OwnerUserId": "5452413"}});